Great and yummy food, I like the mood the place has, and the employees were very kind. Will definitely visit here next time.

Excellent pizza.  Oblong shaped pizza for big square slices. Very interesting toppings.  We love the vegetable slice best, and I have come to love their newer offering, pesto.  You don't want to fold these slices to dilute the delicious taste with too much crust.  I have had the Sicilian rice ball (forgot the name) which was excellent.  Soups are good.  In the winter I especially like the chicken soup, which seems home made.  They have started adding some very good desserts, mainly tarts,, which they display in the front window. When you could sit at tables, they have large bottles of water in the fridge for you to take.  The people who work there are friendly, especially the kitchen guys..  I have found that it would be slightly more pleasant with a warmer approach from the main person at the register.
REALLY good pizza and service! 1010!

Very good pizzeria offering a variety of pizza by the slice or pie. My last two visits included sausage and broccoli rabe followed by a pepperoni slice. N28 is following CDC guidelines for the handling of food. Great service, decent prices excellent selection.

Review for online order. Ordered 2 pizzas today (March 27th), using their website, received email confirmation & card was preauthorised. Waited and waited. No pizza. Looked on seamless, to find they are ‘closed’! Why accept orders?! Want a refund.  Edited: restaurant called to apologize and pizza arrived 3 hours late.

Yum! Great grandma slice which I think might be the crown jewel of New York pizza. Also, disregard bad reviews for delivery. This city is a nightmare to get around and if you want pizza and have two legs to get around go get it yourself.

If you enjoy the by-the-yard carpet samples that pass for ‘great pizza’ at most NYC Pizza joints, you won’t like these guys.  N28 slices are light, savory-spicy and won’t leave you regretting your decision to eat there after three bites.  Also — I ordered three large sheets for a birthday party last month and they arrived hot and on time and every last slice was devoured.  And that’s all I got — all positive.  In fact, I never post to these things.  But when I accidentally landed on this review page just now — and saw all the petty and inane nit-picking going on — it made me mad and I felt duty-bound to defend what I regard as Park Slope’s best pizza.
Good service but the pizza just wasn't that good. The cannolis ,however tasted more traditional and I enjoyed them. If I ever come back it's only for the cannoli.
Great Pizza. Friendly staff. Delicious homemade pasta. But restrooms were not clean.

Meh. There set up is inviting with the pastries by the door. Its alright. The garlic knots are the best thing there. I think there are better places in the area. Never tried their pastas so maybe they do better there.

They use great pizza dough, and the cheese-to-sauce ratio makes the pizza flavorful and light. I ate a slice of Margherita right outside, because you can tell a lot about a place based on their "cheese slice" -- and I am happy to say they passed my test, and I would love to go back.  I strolled by here at 11am after going to the bookshop and I had to go in when I saw they were putting cannolis and fresh baked goods out (haven't tried but want to). I wasn't expecting the place to be as spacious as it was, but there is a large seating section in the back. It seemed a little dark and lonely, so I took my pizza slice outside in the sunshine.  A pizza maker, Daniel, was super sweet, and the host/server Stephanie was extremely informative about how much pizza would feed a party of 8. Just for them I wanted to get delivery but they are a touch overpriced. A whole Margherita pie is $30 and the pepperoni or "Diavola" pie is $38. For context, 2 Boots is $26 for their meatiest pie. I included the menu below since you might be able to sling the "dough."  Overall, I think their per slice is the better option and well worth it.
Very good food

Terrible delivery experience. Everything about our order was wrong. We ordered a pizza and a salad. Pizza arrived ice cold after 90 minutes of waiting. Turns out the store wrote our address down wrong on the delivery ticket (despite us entering it correctly online) which caused an extended delay. The delivery person showed us the wrong address on the ticket.  The salad was supposed to have chicken and no cheese. It arrived with cheese and no chicken.  When I called to complain and ask for a refund the lady answering the phone had a serious attitude and claimed the mishap was due to the weather. Right.  They finally agreed to send somebody back with a refund. Of course nobody showed.

Great pizza if you're in the park slope area. Workers are super friendly and interior is nice. Slices available at the front with a seating area in the back. Also the option of ordering a whole pie to yourself and you can watch it being made in front of you from the dough to when they take it out of the oven. Defenitely worth a try.

The place is small and cute, staff is nice. I like the fact that there are quite a few not so ordinary pizza toppings, like fried onions, feta+spinach, etc., although  it is a bit expensive. The pizza slices tasted OK, but for example the one with feta barely had any feta on it, and if you are not lucky, and don't get a slice from the middle of the pizza, where there are more toppings, then you basically pay for an almost empty crust. Also, it was very oily, and both my husband and I had a stomach discomfort for hours after eating there, I am sure that it happened because of the plenty of oil they use.
